**Slayin gnolls n makin muffins since 3174** <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/utzarothfv.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Tzaroth FV</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 333<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(8/29/02 5:37:56 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2641.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Floating an idea: Deity-specific spells</span><hr size=1> I don't think that Clerics are the class that needs to be focused on. They're already one of the most essential classes in the game. I'm under the impression there are already changes underway that will make them more solo-friendly, so I'm going to have to disagree with some of these proposed examples.<br>
<br>
Bertox and Innoruuk Clerics should not be given Necromancer-ish spells. Clerics are supposed to be the masters of healing. Necromancers are supposed to be the masters of the dead. Now, you're talking about giving Clerics spells that contradict the nature of their profession; you might as well try to give Necromancers the Healing line of spells.<br>
<br>
And what about classes that can't use spells? What will you give to them that makes them feel compensated? Or how about race / classes that can only choose one deity? Example: Iksar Shamans can only follow Cazic-Thule. Will you take away the spells with reference to Vah Shir culture? Beastlords also have some kitty spells, and they're required to worship Thule as well. And if not, why? And what about agnostic characters? The Vah Shir have to be agnostic.<br>
<br>
I'm all for advancement of individuality, but it should be done by personal accomplishment. If a Cleric of E. Marr was to go down into a dungeon and wipe out the NPC SKs of Innoruuk there, they'd be awarded by their God with a spell similar to the nature of E. Marr. Likewise, if they assisted some PC SKs of Innoruuk in clearing out a dungeon of Clerics of E. Marr, then they might have a spell taken away from them.<br>
<br>
That would be an easier, fairer way to decide a character's spell catalog IMHO. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/usyllestraefv.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Syllestrae FV</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>New Mod!</span><br>  Posts: 1089<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(8/29/02 5:44:47 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2641.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Floating an idea: Deity-specific spells</span><hr size=1> Closest you're likely to see is the clickable acolyte/disciple/regent necklaces offered in some (but not yet all) temples.<br>
<br>
It seems they're implemented for all (or close to all) non-human dieties.  The Quellious ones cast lull &amp; pacify n such.  The Brell one boosts your strength or summons stout, etc.<br>
